Within the correlation matrix, we can see that the values of any column or predictor that is greater than or equal to 0.5 must have notable impact on the life expectancy of any given country. Thus, those values are income (approx 0.71), gdpcapita (0.64 approx), healthspend (approx. 0.58), and water (approx 0.826). Also, we must do further investigation on why some values have negative correlation such as childmort (approx -0.91) and chdperwoman (approx. -0.787). We do not count the column greater than 2 because this was previously a TRUE or FALSE column which was converted into a numeric column thus it does not hold any numerical value.

Analyzing the graphs, we observed the following: - Income: As we can see the income for most of the African countries falls within the 0-20000 bracket of income where as other countries are more spread out. Thus, we would like to assign a categorical variable based on their income level and rank them in certain brackets. Additionally, we can see that the graph is right-skewed, indicating the average income is below the mean.

  • GDP capita: Similar to the income graph, this graph also shows that the GDP capita for all of the African countries falls in the 0-20000 bracket. Additionally, European countries seem to have the highest values in terms of this variable. Also, there are two significant outliers in this graph with Europe being the highest and Americas being the lowest (they can be seen in the top right and bottom left corners respectively). For this graph, the skewness is similar to income, meaning more than half of the families earn below the average gdp per capita.

  • Health spend: Based on the graph, we can see that African countries seem to be on the lower end of this variable almost entirely. European countries are much more spread out, and American countries seem to be either mainly on the low end or high end of health spending as both of the outliers in the graph are American countries. Additionally, Asia also seems to be on the lower end of health spending. This is also an extreme case of right-skewed distribution, and a significant majority spend less than a few hundred on their family healthcare.

-Water: Based on the graph, there seems to be a positive correlation between life expectancy and water. In this graph in particular, African countries seem to have a more spread-out distribution whereas European countries seem to clustering towards the higher end. Additionally, Asian countries appear to have higher overall water usage, since there are larger clusters. There is one notable outlier from the Americas that can be seen at the bottom of the graph. Overall, this variable seems significant enough to be included in our regression model.

-Child per woman: Based on the negative correlation in this graph, we can say that as the number of child per woman decreases, the life expectancy increases. This also supports the notion that African countries have low life expectancy rates as the number of child per woman in African countries is relatively higher in comparison to every other continent. A significant outlier that can be seen in the graph is at the bottom from the Americas. In our final model, we end up creating 4 different categories to represent the different levels of this variable.

-Child mortality: Similar to the graph mentioned previously, we can say that as child mortality decreases, life expectancy increases (which is rather obvious but we can confirm this based on the negative correlation of the graph as well). We can also note that child mortality is more prevalent in African countries. One notable outlier in this graph details child mortality in the Americas and we can see it in the bottom right side of the graph. In our final model, we end up creating 4 different categories to represent the different levels of this variable.

Making the Model Description

model1 <- lm(data=df, lifeexp ~  income+healthspend*gdpcapita+chdperwoman*childmort+water)

List of Attempts

  • Attempt 1: Our first order model solely consisted of using income as our first predictor and as expected, the p-value was 0 and was also significant. However, we wanted to obviously add more predictors within the model.

  • Attempt 2: Our second attempt added water as a predictor without any interaction and produced both having a p-value of 0. However, when changed to an interaction model, only water was significant with income and the interaction term being not significant. Thus, we proceeded onwards without any interaction.

  • Attempt 3: Our third attempt resulted in us adding gdpcapita & healthspend which resulted in a worse model with no terms being significant except for water.

  • Attempt 4: Our 4th attempt was adding childmort and chdperwoman to see how they would affect the model but this also resulted in a worse model with less terms being significant and this model had the following: income+water+gdpcapita+healthspend+chdperwoman+childmort -> Thus, we thought we should try seeing which of these columns correlated with each other best in the correlation matrix to try testing for interaction. Income had a 93% correlation with gdpcapita so first we thought, we should test that interaction in our next attempt.

  • Attempt 5: With our 5th attempt, the only significant p-values were water and childmort with the interaction term being insignificant. Next, we tried experimenting in the correlation matrix grouping terms together that posed to be more fit to interacted with such as income and healthspend which had a ~0.94 correlation and childperwoman and childmort with a ~0.85 correlation.

  • Attempt 6: With our 6th attempt, the only insignificant p-values were 3 out of the 9 rows which were healthspend with a p-value of 0.865, income at 0.097, and the interaction term between both at 0.165. Our R-value was 0.908 and the p-value was 0 meaning that the model is significant and with the histogram and QQ plot showing that it is approximately normal.

  • Attempt 7: We now tried further improving our model by creating categorical variables through continous varibles in order to better understand the data and group it. These categories were given based on the plots shown earlier and the values decided from those x-intervals.

Mutating the Model

mutated_df <- df
mutated_df$income_level <- cut(mutated_df$income, breaks = c(-Inf, 20000, 40000, 60000, Inf), labels = c(1, 2, 3, 4))
# Category 1 -> Represents all income levels <= 20000
# Category 2 -> Represents all income levels > 20000 & <= 40000
# Category 3 -> Represents all income levels >= 40000 & <= 60000
# Category 4 -> Represents all income levels > 60000

mutated_df$amountchildren <- cut(mutated_df$chdperwoman, breaks = c(-Inf, 2, 4, 6, Inf), labels = c(1, 2, 3, 4))
# Category 1 -> Represents amount of children <= 2
# Category 2 -> Represents amount of children > 2 & <= 4
# Category 3 -> Represents amount of children > 4 & <= 6

  • Attempt 8: Since we created the new rows, we tried combining them into the regression model by using them as predictors but with no interaction in the model at first which meant that the lm model was “income+income_level+healthspend+gdpcapita+amountchildren+childmort+mort_level+chdperwoman+water”. This was not an ideal model as most of the p-values remained insignificant with many residuals being far from 0 and only 2 p-values being significant which were water (0.017) and childmort (0). R^2 was 0.896.

  • Attempt 9: Trying interaction betweem terms, we decided to test how healthspend and gdpcapita would interact with each other seeing that previously, they had a high correlation with each other. This resulted in a much better histogram with most values being centered or near 0 and R^2 improved to 0.899. Now there were 3 significant p-values with gdpcapita (0.036), amountchildren: 4 being almost significant though at (0.085), childmort (0), and water (0.016).

  • Attempt 10: Now, we want to increase interaction between like terms so now we looked at the interaction between income and income_level. However, this resulted in fewer p-values being significant with only water (0.025) and childmort (0). R^2 was 0.9 and the p-value was 0.

  • Attempt 11: Due to the last result, we now tested 2 different terms which were slightly related previously and instead of chdperwoman interacting with childmort, we decided to test “amountchildren*childmort”. This significantly improved the histogram with many of the results being centered around 0 with only a few outliers in terms of the residuals with the R^2 being 0.92 with a p-value of 0. However, this resulted with only 1 significant p-value with water (0.006)

  • Attempt 12: Now, we tried increasing interaction with our final fix of increasing interaction between most terms: “incomeincome_level+healthspendgdpcapita+amountchildrenchildmort+mort_levelchdperwoman+water”. This resulted in our highest R^2 at 0.922 and with a p-value of 0. Furthermore, multiple terms were significant with income (0.05), gdpcapita almost significant (0.068), water (0.005) and childmort almost significant (0.096).

  • Attempt 13: There seemed to be a lot of collinearity in the model due to the amount of correlation we tried to test out within each interaction term. Thus, in order to have better p-values for most terms, we trimmed down the model to “incomeincome_level+healthspendgdpcapita+childmort*chdperwoman+water”. Doing this resulted in a very large amount of residuals being centered around 0 with a R^2 of 0.91 and a p-value of 0. Furthermore, we now had more significant p-values with gdpcapita (0.043), childmort (0), chdperwoman (0.042), and water (0.004). The interaction term between childmort and chdperwoman also was significant at a p-value of (0).

EXPLANATIONS (for the final model)

#1 - Transformations: Needed or no? The main transformations we had to do for this project were mutating our model. We used the cut() function to create different levels of income, amount of children per woman, and child mortality in order to create 4 different categories for each variable based on levels. This allowed us to create a more precise model. Additionally, we chose not to use some of the individual variables (such as co2) from the original data because those variables did not seem to have a significant enough impact and weren’t necessarily improving the accuracy of our model.
